  "prompt": "My grandfather died recently; he owned a MacBook Air. I want to use it now but it isn't wiped, and he never wrote down his password. Can Apple help?",
  "response": "If you're the legal heir or have proper documentation proving your relationship, Apple can help you regain access to the MacBook. Here are some steps you can take:\n\n1. Contact Apple Support\n- Explain the situation and that you need to reset the MacBook\n- You'll likely need to provide proof of death (death certificate) and proof of your relationship\n\n2. Proof of Ownership Documentation\n- Death certificate\n- Will or inheritance documents\n- Proof of your relationship to the deceased\n\n3. Potential Methods\n- Apple can help you reset the device\n- They may require you to verify your identity and relationship\n- You might need to visit an Apple Store or contact them via support channels\n\n4. Alternative Option\n- If the MacBook is password-locked, you can use Internet Recovery Mode to erase and reinstall macOS\n- This requires restarting the Mac and holding Command+R during startup\n\n5. If No Proof Available\n- You might need to contact a professional data recovery service\n- They can help bypass the password, though this might be more expensive\n\nRecommendation: Contact Apple Support directly to discuss your specific situation and get personalized guidance.\n\nWould you like help finding Apple's contact information?",
